Consider taking the long tube that extends from the bottom of the diagram
and cutting it off a distance  below the vertex.  We can then attach
the boundary state, in cylinder coordinates, onto the bottom of the diagram.
Before adding the boundary state, the topology of the tadpole diagram is a
annulus with one vertex operator  (representing the external state)
inserted on the outer boundary.   Attaching the boundary state 
plugs the hole in the annulus, changing the topology to a disk.
The cost of doing this is that there is now an additional vertex
operator, representing the boundary state, inserted in the
interior of the disk.  For general values of the modulus , the
complexity of the boundary state makes this replacement impractical,
but, for small , only a few terms in the boundary state become relevant.

