                Divergences in the tadpole 


We are now interested in evaluating the tadpole integral
().  At any finite value of , the integrand is a
state in the string Fock space with finite coefficients for each
zero-momentum state.  The matrices  and
 are infinite-dimensional, and while we have expressions
for each matrix element, we cannot analytically compute the integrand
of ().  Nonetheless, by truncating the matrices 
and  at finite oscillator level, we can numerically estimate the
value of the integrand.  Empirical evidence indicates that the
integrand converges exponentially quickly as the level of truncation
is increased, where the rate of convergence depends on the modular
parameter .  For large , we can also consider expanding
() as a function of .  The contribution at
order  represents the portion of the tadpole arising from
the propagation of open string states at level  around the loop.

It is immediately clear from () that the integral for
the tadpole diverges as  due to the term of
order .  This term arises from the propagation of the open
string tachyon around the loop.  In an expansion in terms of the level
of the field propagating around the loop, it is easy to see how this
divergence can be removed by analytic continuation.  Unlike the
divergence from the closed string tachyon considered in the CFT
calculation, the field causing this divergence is explicitly
considered as one of the fundamental degrees of freedom in OSFT, and
thus the associated tachyon divergence can easily be removed by
analytic continuation.  This analytic continuation is most transparent
when we do the calculation level by level in fields.  The method of
level truncation by fields has previously been used in many OSFT
calculations, and is probably the most effective way of dealing with
the open string tachyon; because we are more interested in closed
string physics here, however, we will not pursue this approach further
and we will instead approximate () by truncation in
oscillator level, which leads to a simpler calculation of the
integrand at small .



file=tachyonII.eps,width=16cm 
 vs. .  The straight line plotted has a
  slope of , which is the analytical prediction from section 3. 
 

 From the CFT analysis, we expect to see a divergence in the integrand
of () as .  Indeed, we see numerical
evidence for such a divergence.  Let us first consider the scalar
portion of the state tadpole ,   S_0(T) = e^T (1- S) (1 - S )^13  Q^13   .


Our numerical computations of  are plotted in
figure .  We find that as , 
first increases exponentially, and then falls off, taking a finite
value at .  Both aspects of this behavior have simple
explanations.  The exponential increase is the divergence arising from
the negative mass-squared of the closed string tachyon, and takes the
form .  We can compute the coefficient 
numerically, as we discuss below.  The fall-off occurs because as
 we consider smaller and smaller world-sheet
distances, which require higher and higher oscillator modes to
resolve.  Level truncation essentially acts as a UV cutoff, rendering
the divergence finite as .


 From the conformal field theory analysis, we expect that if we
could compute  to infinite level we would find
  
In figure  we plot the quantity  versus 
 at successively higher levels.  The straight line with slope 
 is the CFT prediction for the infinite level behavior in
the region .  As is evident from the plot, our numerical data
is in good accord with this prediction.  As expected, as the level
increases the region of linear behavior becomes larger, while the
fall-off becomes less rapid, so that successively better estimations of
 are obtained.  

Our data, considered as a function of level, converges exponentially
quickly; that is, to a good approximation, we may write the amplitude
obtained at finite level as eq:LogS  S_0^(L)  (T) =
