As discussed above,
level truncation serves to
render the integrals in equation () finite, 
so that they are calculable numerically.  
The integrands become very sharply peaked near
, so numerical analysis becomes difficult for small .
Nevertheless, it is clear that effects near  give rise to a
violation of qcl .  At successively higher levels, the weight
factor  becomes more and more sharply peaked at , and the
integral is well approximated by its endpoint value 
.  As we have demonstrated above, 
,
while ; these values manifestly fail to satisfy
qcl .  Moreover, as we remove the regularization by sending the
level to infinity, the violation becomes infinite.


We have thus seen in the operator formalism the presence of a
breakdown in BRST invariance which can be directly ascribed to the
presence of short-distance divergences, interpretable in terms of the
closed string tachyon.



                   The infinite level limit 


In this section we look at some of the subtleties of the infinite
level limit of the matrices in the oscillator calculations.
In particular, we are interested in comparing how 
level-truncated calculations
near   compare with what we expect 
if we take the level to infinity.






